Brief introduction on the problem¶

The problem faced by great banks is "Should I rely credit(loan money) to this person?". Most of these problems come from the perennial need to build a house or to buy it from another person. Then banks databases can be a font of information to get the approvation or not. Particularly, people have biased opinion on which aspects are important to make a decision, but to be more assertive it's necessary to take a look on data.

Dataset found at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/devzohaib/eligibility-prediction-for-loan

n Variable Description
1 Loan_ID Unique Loan ID
2 Gender Male/ Female
3 Married Applicant married (Y/N)
4 Dependents Number of dependents
5 Education Applicant Education (Graduate/ Under Graduate)
6 Self_Employed Self employed (Y/N)
7 ApplicantIncome Applicant income
8 CoapplicantIncome Coapplicant income
9 LoanAmount Loan amount in thousands
10 Loan_Amount_Term Term of loan in months
11 Credit_History Credit history meets guidelines
12 Property_Area Urban/ Semi Urban/ Rural
13 Loan_Status (Target) Loan approved (Y/N)

model = ExtraTreesClassifier()
model.fit(X,y)
#print(model.feature_importances_) #use inbuilt class feature_importances of tree based classifiers
#plot graph of feature importances for better visualization
feat_importances = pd.Series(model.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
feat_importances.nlargest(12).plot(kind='barh')
plt.show()

This snippet show us that Credit_History variable is more relevant when we use ExtraTrees as classifier and makes me infer about relevant features in other models.

Using resample technique to balance data¶

In [121]:
from sklearn.utils import resample

df_majority = all_numeric_df[(all_numeric_df['Loan_Status']==1)] 
df_minority = all_numeric_df[(all_numeric_df['Loan_Status']==0)] 
# upsample minority class
df_minority_upsampled = resample(df_minority, 
                                 replace=True,    # sample with replacement
                                 n_samples= 332, # to match majority class
                                 random_state=42)  # reproducible results
# Combine majority class with upsampled minority class
X = pd.concat([df_minority_upsampled, df_majority])
In [123]:
y = X.iloc[:, -1]
X = X.iloc[:, :-1]

Commenting about results¶

In this work I made the common steps in general EDA: read the description, statistic description on each column, checking and handling missing values, univariate, bivariate and almost multivariate(dimensionality reduction wasn't a step I wanted handling with a little amount of data) analysis. After that I transformed categorical columns in numerical and passed it to fit prediction models. Unfortunately the results were better using the simplest method I knew and even so its confusion matrix seemed to indicate overfitting. In conclusion, it's very important to get more data and test other models to improve the quality of the process.
